<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate radiator output at lower water temperatures?", answer: "Radiator output = rated output × (actual dT / rated dT) ^ n, where dT is mean water temperature minus room temperature and n is the radiator exponent (1.30 for panel radiators and fin-tube baseboard, 1.45 for cast iron). Lowering mean water temperature from 160 °F to 120 °F (50 °F drop) cuts panel radiator output to about 50% of rated." },
  { question: "What is rated dT for different radiator types?", answer: "US fin-tube baseboard: rated at 115 °F dT (180 °F water, 65 °F room). US cast iron IBR rating: 100 °F dT (170 °F water, 70 °F room). European EN 442 panel radiators: 50 K dT ≈ 90 °F (70 °C mean water, 20 °C room). Always check the manufacturer data sheet for the specific rating condition." },
  { question: "Why does water temperature matter so much?", answer: "Radiator heat transfer scales with the temperature difference between the water and the room. Hotter water = bigger dT = more output. Dropping from 180 °F to 120 °F cuts output to roughly 40% of rated on a panel radiator. This is why low-temp hydronic systems (heat pumps, condensing boilers) need larger radiators than traditional 180 °F systems." },
  { question: "Can I use a heat pump with regular radiators?", answer: "Yes, but you'll need to either oversize the radiators or accept lower output. A heat pump typically produces 110-120 °F supply water. On a radiator rated for 180 °F water, capacity drops to 30-40%. Solutions: upsize the radiators by 2-3×, run lower flow / higher dT through larger panel radiators, or supplement with radiant floor (which works well at 95-110 °F)." },
  { question: "What exponent do radiators use?", answer: "The dT exponent describes how output scales. Panel radiators (steel, aluminum) tested per EN 442 use n = 1.30. Cast iron uses n = 1.45 because its radiation-dominated heat transfer scales more aggressively with temperature. US fin-tube baseboard uses n = 1.30. Get the exact value from the manufacturer if available; n ≈ 1.33 is a safe default for convection-dominated radiators." }
]) %>

